ce:section.ce:para:
Ultrasonic synthesis is a simple and quickly approach for nano materials synthesis. In comparison with other traditional synthetic approaches, the sonochemical approach could create homogeneous nucleation and a substantial reduction in crystallization time. Without ultrasonic irradiation nonhomogeneous particles can be not separated well and exhibited larger particles (Fig. 3
                        ). The morphology and particle size of sub-micron 1 was investigated under different ultrasonic intensity and time. When the ultrasonic intensity increased from 70 to 100 W, the size of sub-micron decreased from around 5 to 1 μm) (Fig. 4
                        ). This may be due to that high power ultrasound irradiation decreased agglomeration, and thus led to decrease particles size [28]. Under the same ultrasonic intensity of 100 W, more ultrasonic time (40, 60 and 80 min) led to a decreased particle size (1.5, 1 and 0.7 μm) but wider dispersion of particle (Fig. 5
                        ), indicating that long time ultrasound irradiation decreased agglomeration, thus led to decrease particles size.

The chemical resistance sample of 1 (10 mg) was examined by soaking in ethanol and benzaldehyde solution (0.1 M, 10 mL, ethanol as solvent) for 24 h. The experiment PXRD patterns of 1 were good agreement with as-simulated pattern, indicating the integrity of the framework was stable under ethanol condition (Fig. S2). In this work, ground samples (10 mg) of 1 were mixed with ethanol solutions (150 mL) and then ultrasonicated for 5 min to prepare the suspension. To study the selective detection using 1, various solvents (methanol, n-hexane, acetonitrile, N,N-Dimethylacetamide, ethyl acetate, ether, N,N-dimethylformamide, acetone, benzaldehyde (0.1 M, 50 μL, ethanol as solvent)) were added into each suspension (0.067 g/L, 3 mL, ethanol as solvent), respectively. In this regard, the most interesting feature was that the emission intensities of the solvent suspensions were largely dependent on added solvent molecules. When benzaldehyde was added, it exhibited the most distinctly quenching effects in 1 (Fig. 6
                        ). With adding increase concentrations of benzaldehyde, the fluorescence intensities were gradually declined (Fig. 7
                        ). Until the addition concentration of benzaldehyde was the 13 μm, the intensity of CP 1 no longer changed. As illustrated in the previous literature [29], the quenching effect coefficient of 1 was calculated according Stern-Volmer equation 1 (I0/I = 1 + Ksv·[A] (1)), where I0 represented the initial intensity of CP 1 in the absence of analyte, I was the emission intensity in the presence of analyte with molar concentration [A], and Ksv was the quenching constant (M−1). It had an excellent linear relation between intensity and concentration (R2 = 0.9905), the value of Ksv was 4.79 × 105 for 1 at low concentration, illustrating 1 had a sensitive quenching effect towards benzaldehyde.

The chemical resistance of 1 (10 mg) was examined by soaking in Fe3+ solution (0.01 M, 10 mL) for 24 h. The experimental PXRD pattern of sample was good agreement with as-simulated, demonstrating the integrity of the framework under aqueous condition (Fig. S2). The samples of 1 (10 mg) were mixed with aqueous solutions (150 mL) and then ultrasonicated for 15 min to prepare the suspensions. To investigate the potential detection ability of 1 towards various metal ions, including Co2+, Cu2+, Mn2+, Cd2+, Al3+, Ni2+, Fe2+, Zn2+and Fe3+ (as their Cl− salt form). The suspensions of 1 (0.067 g/L, 2 mL) in aqueous solutions were titrated with an equal volume of various metal aqueous solutions (0.01 M, 2 mL), and the emission spectra were obtained (Fig. 11
                        ). From the fluorescence spectra, the luminescence intensity of 1 at 310 nm was quenched completely after the addition of 15 μM Fe3+ solution, whereas other 15 μM metal solutions could not obviously influence the original luminescence intensity of 1 at the same condition. The quenching effect coefficient of 1 was calculated according to equation 1 (I0/I = 1 + Ksv·[A] (1)). It had an excellent linear relation between intensity and concentration (R2 = 0.9963), the values of Ksv was 5.74 × 105 for 1 at low concentration (Fig. 12
                        ), which confirmed its sensitive for selective other metal ions in the aqueous solutions.

It is noted that PXRD patterns did not change during the photo-luminescent sensing process for Fe3+ values by 1 (Fig. S2). In order to confirm the mechanism for coordination polymer’s quenching effect to Fe3+
                        , the UV-absorption spectrum of the Fe3+ ion solution ranging from 240 to 450 nm (Fig. 13
                        ) directly overlapped with the excitation peak of CP 1 (260 nm), which can cause emission quenching of 1 through an excitation energy transfer mechanism. When Fe3+ ions were added into the CP 1 aqueous solution, there would be dynamic collision between Fe3+ ions and coordination polymer. Because the outer electronic structure of Fe3+ was 3d5 and there were five half filed d orbits, the electrons at the conductive band of CP 1 nanosheets would be easily transferred to the half-filled 3d orbits of Fe3+ ions, leading to the significant fluorescence quenching of CP 1. However,’ electronic structure of Fe2+ was 3d6, the electrons at conductive band of CP 1 nanosheets would be hardily transferred to the non-half-filled 3d orbits of Fe2+ ions [30]. Therefore, CP 1 had very unusual and sensitive quenching effect to distinguish Fe3+ and other metal ions especially Fe2+.
